[normal]Appendix E - CJD IP Organs and Tissue Position Statement[bold]CJD Incidents Panel: Organ and Tissue Position Statement – September 2012 [bold][NB The CJD Incidents Panel was dissolved in March 2013]
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction[bold]The CJD Incidents panel developed an organs and tissues statement to capture decisions and discussions arising from the advice considered and given in relation to incidents over a number of years.  The following text was not published but provided an outline from which the Panel and the secretariat could provide consistent advice on any further incidents concerning organs and tissues.  It is intended that this position statement will be reviewed periodically or as required.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Panel should not advise clinicians on the use of organs and tissues donated by people with, at risk of, or with a positive test for CJD or vCJD.  Members considered that Advisory Committee on Safety of Blood, Tissues and Organs (SaBTO) was best placed to give advice on these issues.
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This does not affect the Panel’s advice to ‘at risk’ patients, not to donate organs or tissues.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Incidents involving asymptomatic donors who test positive for vCJD at post mortem, should be managed in the same way as incidents involving donors with symtomatic vCJD.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There was insufficient evidence on tissue infectivity levels to distinguish between the risks posed by different organs and tissues donated by patients with vCJD. Incidents involving all types of tissues and organs from donors with vCJD, including processed and unprocessed bone, should be managed in the same way. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Patients who receive any tissue or organ from donors with vCJD, or donors who test positive for vCJD at post mortem, should be considered ‘at risk’ of vCJD for public health purposes. 
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Patients who receive Haematopoietic stem cells HSC or
[normal] [bold]posterior eye tissues from donors with CJD should be considered ‘at risk’ of CJD for public health purposes. 
[normal]4.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]No actions are required for patients who have received any organs or other tissues from donors with CJD.
[normal]4.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In general, no actions are required for patients who have received tissues or organs from asymptomatic donors ‘at risk’ of vCJD or CJD. The exceptions to this are discussed in the next section ‘Reverse Risks’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Donors of tissues or organs to recipients, who later develop vCJD, should be assessed and managed as if they had donated blood components i.e. as ‘at risk’ for public health purposes.  
[normal]5.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recipients of any other tissues/organs from those donors (who have given tissues/organs to a recipient who developed vCJD), should be assessed and managed as if they had received blood components i.e. as ‘at risk’ for public health purposes.
[normal]5.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Donors of posterior eye tissues
[normal] [bold]or HSC to recipients who later develop CJD, should also be assessed and managed as for vCJD implicated blood components i.e. as ‘at risk’ for public health purposes. No actions are required for donors of organs
[normal] [bold]or other tissues to recipients who later develop CJD.
[normal]5.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recipients of posterior eye tissues or HSC from those donors (who have given posterior eye tissues
[normal] [bold]or HSC to a recipient who developed CJD) should be assessed and managed as for vCJD implicated blood components i.e. as ‘at risk’ for public health purposes. No actions are required for the recipients of organs and other tissues from these donors.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Table 1: Action for organ/tissue recipients: by donor status and organ/tissue type[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Tissue/organ type[bold]Donor status[bold]vCJD case[bold]1[bold]CJD case[bold]2[bold]At risk of vCJD following donation to vCJD recipient[bold]At risk of CJD following donation to CJD recipient[bold]At risk of CJD/vCJD for other reasons[bold]3[bold]Haematopoietic stem cells[bold]Posterior eye tissues[bold]At risk recipient
